            "text": "SELECT * returns every column, including ones the query does not need"
          },
          "ruleId": "SQLT0500"
        }
      ],
      "tool": {
        "driver": {
          "informationUri": "https://github.com/thomasbjork/sqlt",
          "name": "sqlt",
          "rules": [
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Disabled by default; pass `--verbose` / `-v` to surface these. MariaDB constructs that don't yet have a typed sqlparser node — system versioning, FOR SYSTEM_TIME, CREATE PACKAGE, MariaDB sequence option ordering, vector types, DISABLE/ENABLE KEYS, DELIMITER directives, CREATE DEFINER prefixes — are kept as raw text. Same-dialect round-trip preserves them; cross-dialect translation will reject them with a RAW_PASSTHROUGH warning. The `reason` field on the parsed JSON envelope identifies which class of construct triggered the fallback."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0001",
              "name": "raw-passthrough",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "raw"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A statement fell back to raw passthrough — no typed AST in sqlparser 0.59."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "PostgreSQL, MSSQL, and SQLite use double quotes (or square brackets, in MSSQL). Backticks here suggest the SQL was originally written for MySQL and ported without rewriting the quoting style. Pass the SQL through `sqlt translate` to rewrite quoting, or update the source."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0100",
              "name": "mysql-backtick-in-non-mysql",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "dialect-xc"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Backtick-quoted identifiers (`` `id` ``) are MySQL/MariaDB-only."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Other dialects use double quotes or backticks. Most non-MSSQL parsers reject brackets outright; this rule fires under the Generic dialect, which accepts them, and serves as a heads-up that translation to a real target dialect will fail or silently mis-quote."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0101",
              "name": "mssql-bracket-in-non-mssql",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "dialect-xc"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Square-bracket-quoted identifiers (`[id]`) are MSSQL-specific."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "MySQL and MariaDB use `CAST(x AS INT)`. SQLite is loose and accepts both, MSSQL uses `CAST` or `CONVERT`. This rule fires when the AST shows a DoubleColon cast — usually only reachable from Generic or Postgres source dialects."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0102",
              "name": "postgres-double-colon-cast-in-mysql",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "dialect-xc"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`x::int` double-colon cast is PostgreSQL-specific syntax."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "PostgreSQL and SQLite use `ON CONFLICT (...) DO UPDATE SET ...`. MSSQL uses `MERGE`. The MySQL clause will not parse against any other real dialect. `sqlt translate --from mysql --to postgres` rewrites the simple cases."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0103",
              "name": "mysql-on-duplicate-key-in-non-mysql",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "dialect-xc"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE` is MySQL/MariaDB-only."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "MariaDB added RETURNING in 10.5+ for INSERT/REPLACE/UPDATE/DELETE; MySQL has not. If you're targeting MySQL, the clause will be a parse error against the real server (sqlparser parses it leniently). MSSQL uses an `OUTPUT` clause; Postgres/SQLite/MariaDB use RETURNING."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0104",
              "name": "returning-in-mysql",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "dialect-xc"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "MySQL does not support RETURNING on INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE (MariaDB does)."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "MySQL and MSSQL lack RETURNING. `sqlt translate` will drop the clause; under `--strict` the translation fails. If the surrounding code consumes the returned rows, the application will need to fetch them with a separate SELECT."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0200",
              "name": "preflight-returning-unsupported",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "pre-flight"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Target dialect does not support RETURNING on this DML statement."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "MySQL/MariaDB-only. Postgres and SQLite use `ON CONFLICT (...) DO UPDATE SET ...`; MSSQL uses `MERGE`. `sqlt translate` rewrites the simple cases."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0201",
              "name": "preflight-on-duplicate-unsupported",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "pre-flight"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Target dialect does not support `ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE`."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Postgres/SQLite-specific. MySQL/MariaDB use `ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE`; MSSQL uses `MERGE`. `sqlt translate` rewrites the simple cases."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0202",
              "name": "preflight-on-conflict-unsupported",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "pre-flight"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Target dialect does not support `ON CONFLICT`."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "MySQL and SQLite lack named sequences. Use `AUTO_INCREMENT` / `AUTOINCREMENT` on the column, or maintain a counter table by hand. `sqlt translate` will warn and emit the original SQL verbatim."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0203",
              "name": "preflight-create-sequence-unsupported",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "pre-flight"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Target dialect does not support `CREATE SEQUENCE`."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Constructs like WITH SYSTEM VERSIONING, FOR SYSTEM_TIME, CREATE PACKAGE, and vector types fall back to raw text in v1. `sqlt translate` will emit the original SQL with a RAW_PASSTHROUGH warning; the target server will reject it."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0204",
              "name": "preflight-raw-passthrough-unsupported",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "pre-flight"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "MariaDB-specific construct cannot be represented in non-MariaDB targets."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Disabled by default — the emitter renders identifiers using the upstream Display impl, which is generally faithful for the target dialect. Opt-in for cases where you want every quote-style change flagged for review."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0205",
              "name": "preflight-quote-style-mismatch",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "pre-flight"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Identifier quote style won't survive emit to the target dialect."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A comma-separated FROM clause produces a cartesian product unless the WHERE clause filters it down. Even when correct, modern explicit `JOIN ... ON` syntax is much more readable. Mixing comma joins with explicit JOINs (see SQLT0307) is a precedence bug magnet."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0300",
              "name": "implicit-cross-join",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "joins"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`FROM a, b` is a comma cross join — usually unintended."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Cartesian products on real tables are almost always wrong and almost always slow. If you really mean it, add a comment, otherwise add a WHERE clause or convert to an INNER JOIN with an ON predicate."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0301",
              "name": "cross-join-without-where",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "joins"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`CROSS JOIN` with no WHERE clause produces a full cartesian product."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Natural joins use whatever columns happen to share names today. A future schema change adds an unrelated column with a colliding name and the join semantics change without warning. Always use an explicit `ON` or `USING` clause."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0302",
              "name": "natural-join",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "joins"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`NATURAL JOIN` is fragile — adding a column to either table silently changes the join."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Older parsers tolerated `... JOIN tbl` without a constraint and fell back to a cross join. Modern code should always supply an explicit join predicate."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0303",
              "name": "join-without-on",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "joins"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "An INNER/LEFT/RIGHT/FULL JOIN without an ON or USING clause is almost always a bug."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If you want a cross join, write `CROSS JOIN`. A tautological ON predicate is a code smell that usually means the author forgot to fill in the real predicate."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0304",
              "name": "on-tautology",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "joins"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`ON 1=1` (or `ON TRUE`) turns any join into a cross join."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Some dialects fold unquoted identifiers to lowercase; others to uppercase. Quoted identifiers preserve case. Mixing quoted USING column names with unquoted table-side columns can produce subtle case-mismatch bugs. Prefer ON."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0305",
              "name": "using-with-quoted-ident",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "joins"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`USING(\"col\")` with quoted identifiers can disagree across dialects on case folding."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "MariaDB also lacks native FULL OUTER JOIN as of recent releases. Emulate with `LEFT JOIN ... UNION ALL ... RIGHT JOIN ... WHERE l.id IS NULL`. PostgreSQL, MSSQL, and SQLite (3.39+) support it natively."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0306",
              "name": "full-outer-in-mysql",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "joins"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "MySQL does not support `FULL OUTER JOIN`."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Comma has lower precedence than the explicit JOIN keyword in most dialects, so `FROM a, b JOIN c ON c.id = b.id` joins c with b first and then cartesian-products the result with a. Always use one style consistently — preferably explicit JOINs."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0307",
              "name": "comma-join-with-on-elsewhere",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "joins"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Mixing comma joins (`FROM a, b`) with explicit `JOIN ... ON` is a precedence trap."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "SQL three-valued logic strikes again. `x NOT IN (1, NULL)` evaluates to UNKNOWN for every x, not TRUE. Prefer `NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 ... WHERE col = outer.x)`. Schema-aware: when a `CREATE TABLE` for the inner subquery's projected column is present in the same input AND that column is declared `NOT NULL`, the warning is suppressed because the NULL pitfall cannot trigger."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0400",
              "name": "not-in-subquery-null-pitfall",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "subquery"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`NOT IN (SELECT ...)` returns no rows if the subquery yields any NULL."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A correlated EXISTS short-circuits as soon as it finds a match, while many planners materialize an IN subquery into a temporary set first. For single-column subqueries the two are equivalent in semantics; EXISTS is usually preferable. (Schema-blind: the suggestion may be unnecessary if your planner already optimizes IN to a semi-join — measure first if performance matters.)"
              },
              "id": "SQLT0401",
              "name": "in-subquery-prefer-exists",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "subquery"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`IN (SELECT ...)` is often clearer and faster as `EXISTS`."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "`SELECT (SELECT count(*) FROM orders WHERE user_id = u.id) FROM users u` runs the inner subquery once per row in the outer FROM. A LEFT JOIN with GROUP BY or a lateral join is usually faster. Modern planners may rewrite this themselves; measure before assuming the rewrite is a win."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0402",
              "name": "scalar-subquery-in-select",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "subquery"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Scalar subquery in the SELECT list runs once per row — N+1 risk."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Most planners ignore ORDER BY in a subquery whose ordering does not affect the outer result; the few that honor it spend cycles sorting only to throw the ordering away when joining. If you want a top-N within the subquery, add LIMIT."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0403",
              "name": "order-by-in-subquery-without-limit",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "subquery"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "ORDER BY inside a subquery / CTE / derived table without LIMIT is wasted work."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Correlated subqueries run per outer row. Many of them rewrite cleanly to a JOIN with GROUP BY or DISTINCT. Schema-blind heuristic: the linter flags any EXISTS/IN/Subquery in WHERE where the inner SELECT references a compound identifier (e.g. `outer.col`). False positives are possible; treat as a hint."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0404",
              "name": "correlated-subquery-in-where",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "subquery"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A subquery in WHERE that references an outer column may be a JOIN candidate."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Selecting all columns ships unused data over the wire, blocks covering-index plans, and silently picks up new columns when the schema evolves. Enumerate the columns you actually use. Qualified wildcards (`t.*`) after a join are exempt — see SQLT0501. Wildcards narrowed by EXCEPT/EXCLUDE/REPLACE/RENAME also do not fire this rule."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0500",
              "name": "select-star",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "perf"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`SELECT *` returns every column, including ones the query does not need."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Disabled by default — qualified wildcards after a JOIN are often legitimate. Enable with `--rule SQLT0501` to flag every qualified wildcard for review."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0501",
              "name": "select-star-qualified",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "perf"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`SELECT t.*` after a JOIN can hide which columns the query actually needs."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A leading `%` means the optimiser cannot use an index range scan. For real text-search use a full-text index (FTS, MATCH AGAINST, ts_vector, FULLTEXT INDEX) or a trigram index. If you need substring search on a small table, document the intent so the next maintainer doesn't think it's an oversight."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0502",
              "name": "leading-wildcard-like",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "perf"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`LIKE '%foo'` defeats normal B-tree indexes — every row must be scanned."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "`WHERE LOWER(name) = 'alice'` cannot use a btree index on `name`; the planner has to evaluate the function for every row. Either store the lowercased value in a generated column (or trigger), build a functional index, or rewrite the predicate to leave the column bare. Schema-blind heuristic — false positives occur when the column isn't indexed in the first place."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0503",
              "name": "function-on-column-in-where",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "perf"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Wrapping a column in a function inside WHERE typically defeats index plans."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Tagging DISTINCT onto the projection is a common workaround for joins that duplicate rows. Usually a GROUP BY (or EXISTS for a semi-join) is cheaper and more accurate. Worth a closer look if the query is in a hot path."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0504",
              "name": "distinct-as-join-fix",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "perf"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`SELECT DISTINCT` after a JOIN often masks a missing aggregation or EXISTS."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "If the intent is `how many rows`, use `COUNT(*)` (or `COUNT(1)`). If the intent is `how many rows have a non-NULL value in this column`, keep `COUNT(col)` and consider adding a comment so the next reader knows it's deliberate. Schema-aware: when a `CREATE TABLE` for the referenced column is present in the same input AND the column is declared `NOT NULL`, the rule is suppressed because COUNT(col) and COUNT(*) are guaranteed equal."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0505",
              "name": "count-of-nullable-column",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "perf"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`COUNT(col)` skips NULL values; `COUNT(*)` counts every row."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Disabled by default. Implicit casts on column sides of comparisons can defeat index usage and on MySQL silently coerce string columns to numbers (with surprising results). The linter cannot know the column type without schema info; expect false positives. Enable with `--rule SQLT0506` for a focused review pass."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0506",
              "name": "implicit-string-numeric-compare",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "perf"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Comparing a column to a string literal that looks numeric (or vice versa) may force an implicit cast."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Most planners can use one index per pass. An OR across two columns prevents the planner from picking either index, leading to a full scan. Rewriting as `UNION ALL` of two single-column predicates lets each branch use its own index."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0507",
              "name": "or-across-columns",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "perf"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`WHERE a = ? OR b = ?` rarely uses indexes — `UNION ALL` or `IN` is often faster."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "SQL three-valued logic: `col = NULL` is neither true nor false — it's UNKNOWN, so the row is filtered out. Use `IS NULL` or `IS NOT NULL` instead."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0600",
              "name": "equals-null",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "correctness"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Comparing a column to NULL with `=` or `!=` always evaluates to UNKNOWN."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Almost always a mistake. If you really mean to touch every row, add `WHERE TRUE` or otherwise show your intent."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0601",
              "name": "update-without-where",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "correctness"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`UPDATE` without a `WHERE` clause modifies every row in the table."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Almost always a mistake. Use `TRUNCATE` for intentional whole-table wipes, or add `WHERE TRUE` to show intent."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0602",
              "name": "delete-without-where",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "correctness"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`DELETE` without a `WHERE` clause removes every row in the table."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "`AND` binds tighter than `OR`, so `a OR b AND c` parses as `a OR (b AND c)`. Reviewers and reading tools commonly misread it. Parenthesize the AND-side explicitly to make precedence visible."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0603",
              "name": "mixed-and-or-no-parens",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "correctness"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "An `OR` whose operand is an unparenthesized `AND` is a precedence trap."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Positional ORDER BY is brittle: any change to the SELECT list shifts the meaning. Refer to the column by name or alias instead."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0604",
              "name": "order-by-positional",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "correctness"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`ORDER BY <number>` references a projection column by position."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "HAVING is meant to filter aggregated groups. Without GROUP BY there is exactly one implicit group, so HAVING usually means `WHERE`. Some dialects accept this; most readers will misread it."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0605",
              "name": "having-without-group-by",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "correctness"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`HAVING` without `GROUP BY` is almost always a mistake."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Positional GROUP BY is brittle: any change to the SELECT list shifts the meaning. Refer to the column by name or expression instead."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0606",
              "name": "group-by-positional",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "correctness"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`GROUP BY <number>` references a projection column by position."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Postgres and MSSQL require every subquery in FROM to have an alias. MySQL/MariaDB allow it but the resulting plan is hard to read. Add an alias."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0701",
              "name": "unaliased-derived-table",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "style"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A derived table without an alias is rejected by most dialects at runtime."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "note"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "SQL guarantees no row order in the absence of ORDER BY. A LIMIT without ORDER BY may return different rows on different runs (and almost certainly will across replicas, vacuum cycles, or storage layouts). Add an explicit ORDER BY for any page-able query."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0704",
              "name": "non-deterministic-pagination",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "style"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`LIMIT` without `ORDER BY` returns an arbitrary subset of rows."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Floating-point types cannot represent 0.10 exactly. For money use a fixed-point type — DECIMAL/NUMERIC with explicit precision and scale. Heuristic: the rule fires when the column name matches /(price|amount|total|balance|cost|fee)/i. False positives are possible."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0801",
              "name": "float-for-money",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "ddl"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "FLOAT/REAL/DOUBLE for a money-shaped column loses cents to rounding."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "PostgreSQL allows `VARCHAR` with no length and treats it as unlimited. MySQL requires a length. MSSQL silently truncates to 1 character — a classic data-loss bug. Always declare an explicit length: `VARCHAR(255)`."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0802",
              "name": "varchar-without-length",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "ddl"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "`VARCHAR` without an explicit length means different things across dialects."
              }
            },
            {
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Schema-aware rule. Only fires when:\n  * the referenced table is declared via `CREATE TABLE` in the same input,\n  * the reference is qualified (`table.col`, not bare `col`),\n  * the named column is not present on that table.\nConservative on purpose — it never warns about CTEs, derived-table aliases, or tables defined elsewhere. Catches typos and stale references in queries that ship alongside their schema."
              },
              "id": "SQLT0900",
              "name": "unknown-column",
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "sql",
                  "schema"
                ]
              },
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "A column reference of the form `table.col` does not exist on the table's CREATE TABLE."
              }
            }
          ],
          "version": "<X.Y.Z>"
        }
      }
    }
  ],
  "version": "2.1.0"
}
